{"id": "duc04-testb-49:12#36", "contents": "As the Russian parliament rebelled and Yeltsin backed away from his commitments, the United States took a calculated risk, believing it was vastly better that Russia succeed than not succeed, according to Summers. The Russian collapse had far-reaching consequences, triggering economic contagion and huge losses in hedge funds like Long Term Capital, which required a rescue by Wall Street powerhouses. This event marked a turning point, making the world realize that some countries can fail, even with the intervention of the IMF and the Treasury, changing the perception of risk, as noted by Robert Hormats, vice chairman of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co."}
